Doug didn't mention two very important "quirks&features".
The air vents in the cockpit are directly from an airplane. They are not "airplan-ish" or "resembling aviation theme", they are actual air vents used in airplanes.
The other thing is that the V8 is mounted transversally. How many supercars do you know with a transversal engine? Lamborghini Miura? Which one else?

snippet.textDisplay:
The Indonesian hostile takeover did actually happen. That company, Megatech, also owned Lamborghini at that time, which is why the M12 was essentially stretched around a Diablo chassis.

After a year or two Megatech sold Lamborghini to Audi to cover their growing debt. The sale forced them to ironically buy back their own engines, payments for which they eventually defaulted on. That's when they tried buying their way out using a W8.

snippet.textDisplay:
I'm from England, back in October 1992 we were on vacation in Nevada and stayed in Furnace Creek in Death Valley where we stumbled across this very car, along with a silver W9 and another finished in black.
Vector were there to test the cars for high temperature use prior to them being offered to clients in the Middle East.
We got friendly with John from Vector, he was ex Lola cars and very accommodating to the nosy Englishman - I even got to sit in it.
In answer to your question regarding the airbag, I distinctly remember John saying the Vector was the only supercar (of the day) to be fitted with one - no idea why it stuck in my memory but there we are.......
Oh, a transverse mounted engine was an oddity - you'd expect it to be an inline layout like the GT40...
snippet.textOriginal:
I'm from England, back in October 1992 we were on vacation in Nevada and stayed in Furnace Creek in Death Valley where we stumbled across this very car, along with a silver W9 and another finished in black.
Vector were there to test the cars for high temperature use prior to them being offered to clients in the Middle East.
We got friendly with John from Vector, he was ex Lola cars and very accommodating to the nosy Englishman - I even got to sit in it.
In answer to your question regarding the airbag, I distinctly remember John saying the Vector was the only supercar (of the day) to be fitted with one - no idea why it stuck in my memory but there we are.......
Oh, a transverse mounted engine was an oddity - you'd expect it to be an inline layout like the GT40...
